WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.617 --> 00:00:15.527
I'd like to take you back about seven years in my life.
我想带你们回到我大约7年前的生活。

2
00:00:15.870 --> 00:00:20.422
Friday afternoon, a few days before Christmas 2009,
那是2009年圣诞节前几天一个周五的下午，

3
00:00:20.446 --> 00:00:25.596
I was the director of operations at a consumer products company in San Francisco,
当时的我是旧金山一家消费品公司的运营总监。

4
00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:28.830
and I was called into a meeting that was already in progress.
我被叫进一个正在进行的会议。

5
00:00:29.311 --> 00:00:32.303
That meeting turned out to be my exit interview.
我发现这场会议是我的离职面谈。

6
00:00:32.327 --> 00:00:35.337
I was fired, along with several others.
和其他的几个人一样，我被解雇了。

7
00:00:35.910 --> 00:00:38.500
I was 64 years old at the time.
那时我64岁。

8
00:00:39.903 --> 00:00:41.806
It wasn't completely unexpected.
这并不完全出乎我的意料。

9
00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.284
I signed a stack of papers,
我签了一堆的文件，

10
00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:45.890
gathered my personal effects,
收拾了一下自己的东西，

11
00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:47.840
and left to join my wife
就去找我的妻子了，

12
00:00:47.903 --> 00:00:50.468
who was waiting for me at a nearby restaurant,
她在附近的一个小饭店里等我，

13
00:00:50.492 --> 00:00:52.302
completely unaware.
但对此毫不知情。

14
00:00:52.870 --> 00:00:55.488
Fast-forward several hours,
几个小时很快过去了，

15
00:00:55.512 --> 00:00:57.552
we both got really silly drunk.
我们都喝得伶仃大醉。

16
00:00:57.576 --> 00:01:00.347
(Laughter)
（笑声）

17
00:01:00.371 --> 00:01:08.846
So, 40 plus years of continuous employment for a variety of companies, large and small, was over.
就这样，40多年在各个公司间颠沛流离的职业生涯结束了。

18
00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:11.867
I had a good a network, a good reputation --
我拥有很好的朋友圈，人缘也不错

19
00:01:11.891 --> 00:01:13.324
I thought I'd be just fine.
我以为这没什么大不了的。

20
00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:18.816
I was an engineer in manufacturing and packaging,
我曾经是个工作于制造业和包装业的工程师。

21
00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:20.293
I had a good background.
我有很好的从业背景，

22
00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:24.139
Retirement was, like for so many people,
跟很多人一样，退休对我来说，

23
00:01:23.930 --> 00:01:25.910
simply not an option for me,
也算不上是一种选择。

24
00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:28.910
so I turned to consulting for the next couple of years
于是在接下来的几年中我一直做着咨询工作，

25
00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:31.138
without any passion whatsoever.
却没有什么激情。

26
00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:35.227
And then an idea began to take root,
然而后来因为我对环境的关心，

27
00:01:35.251 --> 00:01:38.472
born from my concern for our environment.
我产生了一个新的想法。

28
00:01:39.386 --> 00:01:41.806
I wanted to build my own business,
我想要建立自己的公司，

29
00:01:41.830 --> 00:01:46.148
designing and manufacturing biodegradable packaging from waste --
从废物中设计并生产能进行生物降解的包装，

30
00:01:46.172 --> 00:01:49.172
paper, agricultural, even textile waste --
用以废纸，作物，甚至是纺织废料为原料所制造的包装，

31
00:01:50.291 --> 00:01:56.512
replacing the toxic, disposable plastic packaging to which we've all become addicted.
取代那些人类越来越依赖的，有毒的一次性塑料包装。

32
00:01:56.536 --> 00:01:58.492
This is called clean technology,
这被称作清洁技术。

33
00:01:58.516 --> 00:02:00.526
and it felt really meaningful to me.
它对我而言意义非凡。

34
00:02:00.973 --> 00:02:05.338
A venture that could help to reduce the billions of pounds
这家公司每年能帮助减少数十亿磅

35
00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:12.370
of single-use plastic packaging dumped each year, and polluting our land, our rivers and our oceans,
污染我们的土地，河流和海洋的一次性塑料包装，

36
00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:15.480
and left for future generations to resolve --
它们也会给我们的子孙后代造成困扰——

37
00:02:15.504 --> 00:02:16.867
our grandchildren,
我们的孙辈，

38
00:02:16.891 --> 00:02:18.114
my grandchildren.
我的孙辈。

39
00:02:18.871 --> 00:02:22.371
And so now at the age of 66,
现在我66岁，

40
00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:24.480
with 40 years of experience,
有着40年的工作经验，

41
00:02:24.514 --> 00:02:26.936
I became an entrepreneur for the very first time.
第一次成为了一名企业家。

42
00:02:27.285 --> 00:02:28.382
(Cheers)
（欢呼）

43
00:02:28.406 --> 00:02:31.063
(Applause)
（掌声）

44
00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:31.930
Thank you.
谢谢。

45
00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:34.970
But there's more.
但不仅如此。

46
00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:39.370
(Laughter)
（笑声）

47
00:02:39.488 --> 00:02:41.583
Lots of issues to deal with:
很多事情有待解决：

48
00:02:41.607 --> 00:02:45.987
manufacturing, outsourcing, job creation,
生产，外包，招聘，

49
00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:49.920
patents, partnerships, funding --
专利，合伙人，资金——

50
00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:52.610
these are all typical issues for a start-up,
这些都是创业者面临的典型问题，

51
00:02:52.634 --> 00:02:54.873
but hardly typical for me.
但对我而言并非如此。

52
00:02:54.897 --> 00:02:56.459
And a word about funding.
顺带说下资金。

53
00:02:56.927 --> 00:02:59.522
I live and work in San Francisco,
我在旧金山居住和工作。

54
00:02:59.546 --> 00:03:01.252
and if you're looking for funding,
如果你要寻找资金，

55
00:03:01.276 --> 00:03:06.899
you are typically going to compete with some very young people from the high-tech industry,
那你一般要与一些从事着高科技工作的年轻人竞争，

56
00:03:06.923 --> 00:03:10.434
and it can be very discouraging and intimidating.
这很令人丧气和胆怯。

57
00:03:11.116 --> 00:03:13.529
I have shoes older than most of these people.
我穿的鞋年头都比这些人年纪还要大。

58
00:03:13.553 --> 00:03:19.346
(Laughter)
（笑声）

59
00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:20.521
I do.
确实如此。

60
00:03:20.545 --> 00:03:21.548
(Laughter)
（笑声）

61
00:03:21.572 --> 00:03:23.446
But five years later,
但五年过去了，

62
00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:26.536
I'm thrilled and proud to share with you
我可以兴奋且自豪的告诉大家，

63
00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:29.351
that our revenues have doubled every year,
我们的收入每年倍增，

64
00:03:29.375 --> 00:03:30.883
we have no debt,
没有外债，

65
00:03:30.907 --> 00:03:33.576
we have several marquee clients,
还有一些重要的客户，

66
00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:34.900
our patent was issued,
专利申请也通过了。

67
00:03:34.924 --> 00:03:36.328
I have a wonderful partner
我有一个很棒的合伙人，

68
00:03:36.352 --> 00:03:38.415
who's been with me right from the beginning,
他从最初就和我一起创业，

69
00:03:38.439 --> 00:03:41.498
and we've won more than 20 awards for the work that we've done.
我们的工作已经获得了超过20个奖项。

70
00:03:41.522 --> 00:03:43.279
But best of all,
不过最好的是，

71
00:03:42.830 --> 00:03:44.870
we've made a small dent --
我们缓解了——

72
00:03:44.748 --> 00:03:45.947
a very small dent --
微不足道地缓解了——

73
00:03:45.971 --> 00:03:49.343
in the worldwide plastic pollution crisis.
世界塑料污染危机。

74
00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:54.010
(Applause)
（掌声）

75
00:03:54.970 --> 00:04:00.860
And I am doing the most rewarding and meaningful work of my life right now.
而我现在做着一生中回报最为丰厚、最有意义的工作。

76
00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:07.160
I can tell you there's lots of resources available to entrepreneurs of all ages,
我可以告诉大家，对各个年龄阶段的企业家，都有很多可利用的资源。

77
00:04:07.071 --> 00:04:14.672
but what I really yearned for five years ago was to find other first-time entrepreneurs who were my age.
但过去五年我最渴望的事情是找到其他与我同龄的，第一次创业的企业家，

78
00:04:14.696 --> 00:04:17.546
I wanted to connect with them.
我想和他们取得联系。

79
00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:20.305
I had no role models, absolutely none.
那时我没有可以参考的榜样，完全没有。

80
00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:23.530
That 20-something app developer from Silicon Valley
硅谷那位20多岁的应用程序开发者

81
00:04:23.578 --> 00:04:25.148
was not my role model.
可不是我的榜样。

82
00:04:25.172 --> 00:04:26.173
(Laughter)
（笑声）

83
00:04:26.197 --> 00:04:27.700
I'm sure he was very clever --
我确信他很聪明。

84
00:04:27.724 --> 00:04:29.129
(Laughter)
（笑声）

85
00:04:28.910 --> 00:04:30.580
I want to do something about that,
所以，我想改变一下现状，

86
00:04:30.844 --> 00:04:33.123
and I want all of us to do something about that.
我希望所有人都可以有所行动。

87
00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:39.200
I want us to start talking more about people who don't become entrepreneurs until they are seniors.
我希望我们可以更多的谈论那些直到老年才成为企业家的人。

88
00:04:39.165 --> 00:04:42.083
Talking about these bold men and women who are checking in
多谈论这些勇敢的人，当他们的同龄人退休时，

89
00:04:42.107 --> 00:04:44.703
when their peers, in essence, are checking out.
他们才开始正式入行。

90
00:04:45.343 --> 00:04:49.191
And then connecting all these people across industries, across regions,
然后，将所有这些跨行业、跨地区、

91
00:04:49.215 --> 00:04:50.858
across countries --
跨国家的人联合起来，

92
00:04:50.882 --> 00:04:52.047
building a community.
组成一个社区。

93
00:04:52.369 --> 00:04:54.856
You know, the Small Business Administration tells us
小企业管理局数据显示

94
00:04:54.880 --> 00:05:00.089
that 64 percent of new jobs created in the private sector in the USA
在美国，64%的私企提供的新岗位

95
00:05:00.113 --> 00:05:02.794
are thanks to small businesses like mine.
是像我这样的小企业创造的。

96
00:05:03.416 --> 00:05:05.962
And who's to say that we'll stay forever small?
并且谁敢说，我们会一直维持这个规模？

97
00:05:06.387 --> 00:05:08.356
We have an interesting culture
我们有个有趣的文化，

98
00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:12.490
that really expects when you reach a certain age, you're going to be golfing, or playing checkers,
当你到了一定的年龄，就得去打高尔夫、下棋、

99
00:05:12.490 --> 00:05:15.130
or babysitting the grandkids all of the time.
照顾孙子，在这些方面倾注所有。

100
00:05:15.642 --> 00:05:18.546
And I adore my grandchildren --
我很爱我的孙辈。

101
00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:19.620
(Laughter)
（笑声）

102
00:05:20.377 --> 00:05:22.384
and I'm also passionate
可我也充满了热忱，

103
00:05:22.408 --> 00:05:25.782
about doing something meaningful in the global marketplace.
希望为全球市场贡献自己的一份力量。

104
00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:28.770
And I'm going to have lots of company.
我还会开很多公司。

105
00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:31.369
The Census Bureau says that by 2050,
美国人口普查局表示，到2050年，

106
00:05:31.393 --> 00:05:34.672
there will be 84 million seniors in this country.
美国会有8400万老年人。

107
00:05:35.397 --> 00:05:37.621
That's an amazing number.
这个数字非常惊人，

108
00:05:37.645 --> 00:05:40.283
That's almost twice as many as we have today.
几乎是现在的两倍。

109
00:05:40.307 --> 00:05:45.431
Can you imagine how many first-time entrepreneurs there will be among 84 million people?
可以想象，到时候在这8400万人中会有多少首次创业者吗？

110
00:05:45.893 --> 00:05:48.472
And they'll all have four decades of experience.
他们都有40年的工作经验。

111
00:05:48.496 --> 00:05:50.291
(Laughter)
（笑声）

112
00:05:50.315 --> 00:05:55.731
So when I say, "Let's start talking more about these wonderful entrepreneurs,"
所以，当我说“让我们更多的谈论这些优秀的企业家，”

113
00:05:55.755 --> 00:05:58.895
I mean, let's talk about their ventures,
我的意思是，让我们谈论他们的冒险精神，

114
00:05:58.919 --> 00:06:02.483
just as we do the ventures of their much younger counterparts.
就像我们谈论那些年轻创业者的冒险精神一样。

115
00:06:03.300 --> 00:06:10.743
The older entrepreneurs in this country have a 70 percent success rate starting new ventures.
在美国，年长的创业者有70%的成功机会去建立新的事业。

116
00:06:10.767 --> 00:06:12.771
70 percent success rate.
70%的成功机会。

117
00:06:13.227 --> 00:06:16.244
We're like the Golden State Warriors of entrepreneurs --
我们就像创业者中的金州勇士（美国西部职业篮球队）一样。

118
00:06:16.268 --> 00:06:17.486
(Laughter)
（笑声）

119
00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:19.941
(Applause)
（掌声）

120
00:06:19.965 --> 00:06:24.790
And that number plummets to 28 percent for younger entrepreneurs.
而在年轻人中，这个数字只有28%。

121
00:06:24.814 --> 00:06:28.288
This is according to a UK-based group called CMI.
这是一家英国组织CMI公布的数据。

122
00:06:28.833 --> 00:06:33.328
Aren't the accomplishments of a 70-year-old entrepreneur every bit as meaningful,
难道一个70岁创业者的成就不同样有意义，

123
00:06:33.352 --> 00:06:34.690
every bit as newsworthy,
同样有新闻价值吗？

124
00:06:34.714 --> 00:06:37.831
as the accomplishments of a 30-year-old entrepreneur?
和一个30岁的创业者没什么不同。

125
00:06:37.855 --> 00:06:39.242
Of course they are.
当然应该是这样。

126
00:06:39.266 --> 00:06:44.122
That's why I'd like to make the phrase "70 over 70" just as --
这也是我为何要用这个词“70大杰出老人”——

127
00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:44.900
(Laughter)
（笑声）

128
00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:48.850
just as commonplace as the phrase "30 under 30."
就像大家通用的“30大杰出青年”一样。

129
00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:49.870
(Applause)
（掌声）

130
00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:50.930
Thank you.
谢谢大家。

131
00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:52.110
(Cheers)
（欢呼）

132
00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:56.500
(Applause)
（掌声）